<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="REI01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">William Hamilton</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Reid</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1784"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1827"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">poet</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">controversialist</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">One of the more mercurial and shadowy figures of London radical
    circles who moves from radicalism to loyalism and back. The links in the diary make the identification plausible. He is associated with visits to 
      <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="MUI01">Muir</persName> and <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="PAL01">Palmer</persName> after their
    trials, then a series of links through <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="PHI01">Phillips</persName> and publishing circles; then a group associated
    with attendance at Hazlitt's lectures and with <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HAZ01">Hazlitt</persName>. We cannot be certain that this is the
    Reid whom Godwin notes but it seems highly likely that Godwin would have made his acquaintance -
